---
import ToolPage from '../../layouts/ToolPage.astro'
import HashGeneratorIsland from '../../islands/HashGeneratorIsland'
import { getToolMeta } from '@devkits/core'

const meta = getToolMeta('hash-generator')!
---

<ToolPage meta={meta}>
  <HashGeneratorIsland client:load />

  <section class="mt-12 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-4">How to Use</h2>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none text-sm leading-relaxed space-y-3">
      <p>
        Type or paste the text you want to hash into the input field, then select an algorithm —
        <strong>MD5</strong>, <strong>SHA-1</strong>, <strong>SHA-256</strong>, or
        <strong>SHA-512</strong>. The hash digest is computed instantly as you type and displayed
        in lowercase hexadecimal. Click the copy button to place the hash on your clipboard.
      </p>
      <p>
        Practical use cases include verifying file integrity by comparing expected and actual
        checksums, generating deterministic cache keys from request parameters, producing
        content-based identifiers (content-addressable storage), and cross-checking published
        SHA-256 digests when downloading software packages or container images.
      </p>
      <p>
        All hashing runs locally in your browser using the Web Crypto API. No input text is ever
        transmitted externally, making this safe for hashing internal strings or configuration
        values.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">Is MD5 still safe to use?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          MD5 is cryptographically broken and should not be used for security-sensitive purposes
          such as password hashing, digital signatures, or certificate fingerprints. It remains
          acceptable for non-security tasks like generating cache keys or checksums where collision
          resistance is not critical.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">What is the difference between SHA-256 and SHA-512?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Both are members of the SHA-2 family and are considered secure. SHA-256 produces a
          256-bit (64 hex character) digest, while SHA-512 produces a 512-bit (128 hex character)
          digest. SHA-512 offers a larger security margin and can be faster on 64-bit CPUs, but
          SHA-256 is more widely supported and sufficient for most applications.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">Can I use this tool to hash passwords?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          No. General-purpose hash functions like SHA-256 are designed to be fast, which makes
          them unsuitable for passwords. Password hashing requires a deliberately slow algorithm
          such as bcrypt, scrypt, or Argon2, which resist brute-force and dictionary attacks by
          making each attempt computationally expensive.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">How do I verify a file's SHA-256 checksum?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Compute the SHA-256 hash of the downloaded file (using this tool or the
          <code>sha256sum</code> command on Linux/macOS) and compare the result character-by-character
          against the expected checksum published by the software vendor. Any difference indicates
          the file was corrupted or tampered with.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</ToolPage>
